post_text: While students are participating in distance learning through September 25, Student Dining Services will provide meal packages that contain breakfast and lunch items for five (5) days. Meal distribution will take place outside of each school building from noon – 4 p.m. on Wednesdays, starting August 26. Students enrolled at a CPS' Community Eligibility Schools will receive free meals. Students who are enrolled in all other CPS schools and who are paid-meal eligibility status will be charged $8.75 for an elementary school meal pack or $10.00 for a secondary school meal pack per USDA regulations. To learn more, visit https://buff.ly/3j31xT2

post_text: This August and September, we will be offering grape tomatoes from two local farms in our remote meal packs! Riehm Produce Farm is a fifth generation family farm in Tiffin, OH, and Salad Days Farm is located in Versailles, KY and is USDA Certified Organic. Visit us at any of our schools on Wednesdays between 12-4pm, August 24th - September 23rd to pick up a remote meal pack!

post_text: Congratulations to recent graduates, Jaelynn Gentry (Withrow University High School), Aissatou Barry (Taft Information Technology High School) and Lauren Gibson (School for Creative and Performing Arts, this year’s Superintendent's Housing Award recipients. The Award is a one-time, $600 stipend that can be used to buy necessities for dorm rooms, classroom equipment or other expenses for which scholarship funds cannot be used. The effort represents a personal commitment of Superintendent Mitchell to ensure that CPS students are supported as they transition to higher education.

post_text: Tonight is the night! Cincinnati Public Schools’ Jazz Academy will present a live concert on our YouTube channel at 8:00 p.m. The concert will feature 12 professional musicians from Cincinnati performing live from the Kennedy Heights Arts Center. Our CPS Jazz Academy students will be watching via livestream on YouTube, and will be sending in questions that will be answered live. The concert honors the lives and music of six important African American jazz musicians: Bessie Smith, Ferdinand “Jelly Roll” Morton, Duke Ellington, Mary Lou Williams, Charlie Parker and Wes Montgomery. Be sure to tune in to our YouTube channel this evening at 8:00 p.m.

post_text: This morning, the Cincinnati Board of Education received an update on the District’s Safety Plan for Reopening Schools. We are committed to educating our students in as safe an environment as possible. As a result, our plan addresses all of the Considerations for Schools outlined by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention: Behaviors that Reduce Spread, Maintaining Healthy Environments, Maintaining Healthy Operations and Preparing for When Someone Gets Sick. It paints a picture of what Cincinnati Public Schools will look like for students and staff in the fall. Review the plan: https://bit.ly/2C8pFDF

Cincinnati Public Schools will reopen its school offices starting today, mainly for the registration and enrollment of students for the 2020-21 school year. Elementary schools will be open Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. High schools and K-12 buildings will be open Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays from 11 a.m. to 3 p.m.

Health and safety guidelines from the Ohio Department of Health will be followed inside all CPS buildings, including limiting the number of people allowed inside. All employees and visitors must wear face masks, and follow social distancing guidelines — standing or sitting a minimum of 6-feet apart.

post_text: Cincinnati Bell, Cincinnati Public Schools (CPS), Greater Cincinnati Foundation, United Way of Greater Cincinnati, and ComputerXpress are partnering with several organizations to help thousands of K-12 public school students in Cincinnati and Northern Kentucky access low-cost Internet connectivity at home in time for the 2020-21 school year. The program will deliver connectivity to approximately 2,000 qualifying students from five CPS schools who currently lack Internet access: Rockdale Academy, South Avondale School, Hays-Porter Elementary School, Roberts Academy, and Fairview Clifton German Language School. Learn more: https://bit.ly/2zoaa9o

post_text: Cincinnati Public Schools is launching CPS Students Speak Up and Speak Out, the first in a series of forums for students, by students, to discuss racial injustice and inequities in our city and country. Community leaders will come together to dialogue with our student leaders on how we can effectively make true progress and support them through this time of injustice and racism. To join the conversation on Wed., June 3 at 12p, visit https://bit.ly/3gMlUTT and enter Event ID: rvehxjjw

post_text: Cincinnati Public Schools, in partnership with iconic Cincinnati institutions, will collect this year’s graduating seniors' experiences of the COVID-19 pandemic through the Class of 2020 Legends project. The project, housed at https://bit.ly/2zjlTWD, with many submissions to be later archived at the Cincinnati History Museum, will feature music, stories, videos, photographs, poetry, original dance and artwork reflecting their experiences. The Cincinnati Museum Center, National Underground Railroad Freedom Center, Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra, Cincinnati Pops, May Festival and Cincinnati Art Museum, will celebrate, recognize and provide free tickets, admissions or memberships to the more than 1,907 graduating seniors, from the 16 CPS high schools, who choose to participate. For more information, visit https://bit.ly/3cT1rue.

Tomorrow, students will be allowed access to buildings to gather their belongings. A schedule has been created according to students' last names. CDC recommended protocols must be followed:

-Temperatures must be taken prior to arrival.
-If you have a fever or cough, please stay home.
-Wear a face mask or a cloth covering your nose and mouth. No face mask, no entry.
-Maintain social distancing, keeping a minimum of 6 feet apart.
-Wash hands frequently for a minimum of 20 seconds.

For the complete schedule, visit https://bit.ly/2WfIg6V

Hey students and families. We will be allowing students to return to schools to gather their belongings next Tuesday and Thursday. There are specific times for students to arrive based on last names. It is important to come only during your scheduled time. Enter using the main doors. All other doors will be locked.

CDC recommended protocols must be followed:

-Temperatures must be taken prior to arrival.
-If you have a fever or cough, please stay home.
-You MUST wear a face mask or a cloth covering your nose and mouth at all times. No face cover, no entry.
-Maintain social distancing, keeping a minimum of 6 feet apart.
-Wash hands frequently for a minimum of 20 seconds.

To find out your scheduled time, visit https://bit.ly/3d3Vbzv

post_text: Western & Southern Financial Group has announced that Stacey Hill-Simmons, principal at Evanston Academy, has been named the 2020 Dr. Lawrence C. Hawkins Educator of the Year. She will receive a plaque and a personal check for $10,000. Under her leadership, Evanston Academy earned an overall grade of 'A' on its report card issued by the Ohio Department of Education in September 2019. Congratulations to Ms. Hill-Simmons!

Attention high school juniors! If you do not have access to a computer or device for your school work, you can come to any of four locations on Friday, April 24, 2020, between 10:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. The school locations that will be distributing iPads are Midway School, Aiken High School, Woodward Career Technical High School, and Shroder High School.

iPads will be distributed following the recommended guidelines of the Centers for Disease Control, Gov. DeWine and the Ohio Health Department. When you arrive please pull up in the front driveway or parking lot and a CPS technician will greet you with instructions.

The distribution begins with 11th-graders on April 24, followed by lower grades on this schedule:

• 10th-graders — Monday, April 27
• 9th-graders — Wednesday, April 29
• 8th-graders — Friday, May 1
• 7th-graders — Monday, May 4

CPS students who are unable to come on the designated day can come on another distribution day. For more information: https://buff.ly/2xTASGc

post_text: Today, Gov. Mike DeWine announced the closure of school buildings through the end of the school year. For Cincinnati Public Schools, the last day for students is May 21, 2020. And, while buildings are closed, learning continues! Our educators and staff continue to be your number one resource. Our remote learning plan is available at http://remotelearning.cps-k12.org. It is designed to help make remote learning easier. Enrichment Learning Packets include content for the remainder of the year. Our meal hubs will continue to serve breakfast and lunch to our students. We will come through this stronger than ever before, and when the day comes to return to our school buildings, we will bring much of what we’ve learned with us. Thanks to you, our parents and families, along with our incredible staff and community partners, we are #CPSUnited.

post_text: Our new Remote Learning portal has a special section for high school seniors to help them achieve their graduation goals. In addition to lessons to continue learning, we have information about credit recovery, graduation requirements and more. To ensure that your senior achieves their graduation goals, visit https://buff.ly/34nRSAc

post_text: Today is the day! We are distributing Enrichment Learning Packets at all of our meal hub locations. These packets are especially for students who do not have access to the Internet at home. If your student needs a packet, please stop by one of our meal hub locations between 11am and noon today. Thanks to Valerie Vasquez for the photo. To find a list of meal hub locations, visit https://buff.ly/34zHOUL.
